<Text>These guys are insanely expensive!
We waited until the last minute to file our taxes because we knew we would owe. Instead of filing for an extension, like we should have done, we decided to bite the bullet and go. While the staff were very polite, our tax preparer wasn't exactly thrilled with our hot mess we presented to him. Now, while I understand we should have gone in earlier or filed the extension, this is his JOB, right? He is getting paid to do a job, and do it right. He obviously didn't feel this way. Long story short,  we ended up paying almost  $600 when we were told roughly 450 and we owe almost 17k. We were upset so we went back to the CPA that we used to use (and should have gone to in the first place) and he can already alleviate at least $600 from what we owe. H&R block only cares about 1 thing, how much money they can squeeze out of you.< /Text>< pictures>

<Rating>4</Rating>< Text>
I don't have much to say on this one except for the turkey burger. It's what I always get. It's very good. It's why I go there. I've had the basic burgers which are good too in a traditional burger sense but I'm a creature of habit when it comes to Pearl's. My friends rave about the specialty burgers which one day I might try but they're huge!

50's style place, limited seating but once you're in, it's comfortable and the people that work there are always, and I mean always nice and helpful. I've seen many of the same people there for years which is a good sign for an establishment.

Probably the defining moment for me at Pearl's was standing in line with Robin Williams a number of years back. He liked Pearl's too.< /Text>

What they have done for my family I will never forget. Their Dr's are so competent they noticed a new heart condition on a dental check on my 12 year old Pit. Because she was concerned, we saw a cardiologist before they would do dental surgery, rather than just take my money and put my dogs life at risk. We got the appropriate consult and started her on a new medication, new food and overall healthier regimen. We rescheduled for dental surgery and they blocked out a large portion of their day on a friday to ensure they had all hands on deck in case something happened to her while she was under. Words can not describe how much this meant to me and our family. She and her adopted brother are safe, surgery was beautifully successful and the cost was astonishingly lower than any other vet I have ever visited. They have made a life long patient from our family. Thank you so much to all of their staff, you are truly the best.< /review>

< review>
We recently adopted a puppy, so we needed to schedule her for an initial exam. We took her to another vet, and were very disappointed with the doctor. I decided to take her to another vet to get an actual exam, and after calling around I made an appointment with Laguna Creek. The front office staff was very friendly when I called, and again friendly the day of our appointment.

We saw Dr. Purewal for the exam, and he was fantastic! He did a thorough exam of our pup, and because we're first time dog owners, he took time to share all sorts of helpful information and answer all of our questions. What was even more impressive, my 10 year old daughter came to the appointment with me, and he explained everything to her, as well.

All of this was worth 5 stars, but I had to deduct one star. I called a few days later to schedule an appointment because my pup had injured her leg and was limping. I called on a Thursday morning, and the soonest they could see her was Monday. Obviously we couldn't wait that long, so I had to take her to another vet. It would be nice if they were able to schedule same day or next day appointments for something that requires immediate attention.<//review>

<time>1490138735201<//time><Gmap_id>0x809ac89defe1054d:0xd80d163b42e6224f<//Gmap_id>< review>
While the staff was friendly and involved, and the facility itself was clean and well kept, I had a bad experience overall.  (Note: this was my first experience with this veterinarian.)

I scheduled my cat for a check-up when I noticed he started spinning in one direction instead of standing still or walking straight.  After talking with the doctor she took him in the back to do some tests in order to determine what the issue was.  Outward, there was nothing wrong with my cat. So they gave him some anti-nausea medicine and told me to keep an eye on him.

That same day I had to rush him to an emergency vet when he started having seizures.  Less than 4 days later I had to put him down.

While this vet wasn't equipped to handle brain/emergency cases, it wasn't until later I realized that the first minor focal seizure actually happened AT THIS VET while she was talking to me about what they found, or rather, didn't find and she didn't recognize it as such.  I know in my head that even if they were to have caught it right then and we wouldn't have delayed those 5-6 hours it wouldn't have made a difference.

Unfortunately, this left a bad impression on me and I'm finding it hard to go back to them.< /review>

<Review>I absolutely love Laguna Creek Veterinary Hospital.

< Text>
I came home to find my Holland Lop bunny with an injured leg. I immediately called many vets that weren't able to treat bunnies. It was late in the day and i was getting concerned he wouldn't be able to be seen. I called laguna creek and they were able to treat bunnies and could take him in right away. After xrays determined his leg was broken she explained how to treat, what to expect and when to call her if something was not right. I felt the cost of the emergency visit and xray were very reasonable. Thank to Dr. Layton and her staff, it is lucky to find such caring people.</Text>

I work at a place that sells pet products and I know a thing or two about what kind of medicine is good or bad, what kind of flea medication is the best and so on. Oh yes and I also know what a SENSIBLE HARNESS is...because my dog has one and the clip goes on the front of the dogs chest. My dog is generally happy, she rarely growls at people, she's a huge people lover, but she didnt like this Dr. She must not like DOUCHE BAGS that much. <user_id>117770725180971522214</user_id><username>Barbara Price</username>< rating>
4</rating>
<gmap_id>0x80857ecd03fd63b1:0x2290f36ac9a50e39</gmap_id>< date>
1551645507858</date>
</record>
</dataset><record>
<Rating>3< /Rating><Resp>{'time': 1525462490858, 'text': 'Thank you for considering Belmont Village. We understand the importance of finding the right fit and we wish you the best of luck in your search.'}<//Resp><gmapID>0x80857ecd03fd63b1:0x2290f36ac9a50e39</gmapID>< Pics>
None</Pics>
< date>
1525088180010</date>
< text>
I visited this place five times, twice for meals, and went through their admissions process. Each time I entered the huge entry room I felt depressed. It has a large piano with canned tinkling music emanating from its insides and fake flowers dotted around. I never saw more than one-three individuals sitting in the vast space.
There was never a sense that there is any sort of spontaneous community there. I saw very few people going in or going out.  Maybe there is a back door to a parking lot I missed.

On reading their literature it seems one woman developed the three-tiered concept in another state from her Alzheimer's father needing care. Thus, the 'independent living' folks seem, to an outsider, to be pulled down into dependency by that original origin. That is, I originally thought it was a way for older adults to 'age in place' and do everything they would do if they lived in their own homes, but feel secure 'in case' they ever needed more care, but I then saw it as actually starting with the idea that they DO need more care. The managers, a nurse and a longtime former HR manager at a hotel (completely different skills from managing an independent community) seem to see the 'independent livers' as needing their 'care' from the start. For instance, they want to know if and what medicines the independent residents take so they can have someone monitor them. ('You'd be surprised how many people forget to take their medicines'.) There is a rule that a staff person goes into each apartment two (2!) times a day to 'collect the trash' A resident I sat with at dinner suggested it was due to nosiness. Otherwise, such intrusiveness makes no sense. -- All the staff have keys to each apartment.

The last two choices of apartments available were very small and have only a view of a wall or busy, unpretty San Pablo Ave.

I was shown a large concrete patio (I was told there are more!) with sad small trees in places which I would never be drawn to sit in. I didn't see a garden for planting or enjoying outside, nothing to invite resident participation. No people were in this one and I bet people rarely if ever went there.

I didn't see pets and doubt they are allowed.

I didn't see a single child during each of my visits. Who is it who thinks that old people need to be only with other old people?

They seem to think elders want to be pampered. The dining area (two meals a day are paid for) is built like a restaurant, with orders taken by waitresses. There is a long wait. The food was good enough the two times I ate there. My daughter came with me once and ordered salmon which turned out to be farmed. I didn't ask what percentage of the food is organically grown but I doubt it is high..One resident told me she could get brown rice if she asked for it. Real-life examples of food available for choosing was set out at the entryway to the dining area; I felt hurt at the waste that caused every single day.

A friend's husband with Alzheimer's stayed there for a time. But she felt she had to go and feed him three times a day because he wasn't getting properly fed by the caretakers. She paid over $8000/month for his care.

I felt patronized, by both the nurse and the former Human Resources manager.

I missed an art room; the idea that residents create their own programming; spaces with nature to walk in and work in; and natural indoor design rather than a sense that decor is there to impress.  Thr architecture is not designed for light and nature. There was no bustle and no sense of friendly, spontaneous community. Even the waitresses didn't say hello though I had interacted with them at lunch before. They didn't speak to the residents either

The managers exude a sense of knowing what's best for residents.  I felt smaller having been there, shrunken, didn't see how I could take a deep breath and expand  It is definitely designed for 'the last years' and one could see the end. As a longtime former trauma and family psychotherapist and educator, I could imagine my last years cut in half if I moved in there. So I didn't.<//text>

S THOMSON< /user_name>

<Rating>5< /Rating>< text>
Everything was perfect. We had a great guy guiding us through the vineyard and answering our question perfect. We also had the opportunity to meet the founder and he was nice to us and took time to talk for a while. And the wines were really good as well and as other have reviewed before - they offer a small and intimate tasting room that wasn't crowded at all.

If you're looking to visit a vineyard in the area - this is the place. They also gave us recommendations of lunch afterwards and that place was also great (Sides, Los Olivos, CA).

Just go here!</text>

<user_id>111982108850766961594< /user_id><username>Larry Erbert<//username><date>1426874826442<//date><rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Seriously incredible experience at Beckman Vineyards.  Victoria was amazing and the wines were the best we have had in California! The philosophy, practices, and management of this vineyard are ways of moving forward in a sustainable world that all should embrace.  Prior to our afternoon at Beckman's, we visited a vineyard featured in the movie Sideways, and every wine was mediocre.  When we arrived at Beckman's the 8 wines we tasted exceeded our expectations--I don't want to oversell, but every wine we tasted was absolutely perfect for us.  You do not want to miss these wines if you are near Santa Ynez wine country!!< /Review>

Beautiful camping grounds! Awesome that they have a FREE camping area! You just pull in your car. Almost every spot has its own fire pit and water spicket, also had paths that led down to the water. Perfect for my girl and I for a little spur of the moment romantic getaway! (Even without the tent,  and just being in the car!)<//review>

101205298764784732777< /user_id>
< Name>
Play Hard</Name>
<date>1604813748837</date><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
There is 2-3 trains every 1 ¬Ω-2hrs that last atleast 5min long each time pass that goes all day all night. The trains have different schedules every day. Sometimes no train and they pass at different times. But if u dont mind it, its really quiet between those times (not so many people) depending on the month u choose, like winter before they close the park on november 15th. Limit of days to stay is 14. We didnt experience any wild animal run ins except fecies of a small animal in many spots on the street path and one huge pile of Bear fecies by our campsite (#2) next to drinking water faucet; which there are alot of drinking water faucets in the campground.Some campsites are private and most are very open. 3 bathroom locations; one in beginning, 2nd in middle of park and 3rd at far end where it is much colder cause of the closeness of water. A river at each side. There is fishing. Clean bathrooms; toilet and sink. Marked men and women in the middle bathroom. Lots of paths to walk through. Beautiful. Host was amazing! I forgot his name but he was a older gentleman that had a long white beard that reached a pretty good distance.$15 a night. No day use. Big spaces for rv pull ins. Very dark/blinding at night, only lights are outside/inside bathrooms so bring flash lights & batteries.Closest market is super expensive so bring lots $$ but u are supporting it locally and they do have great burritoes and good selection of groceries including fruits.</Review>

<Review>Toilets and floor were very clean. The history trail around the campground was interesting and fun. Standing on the old suspension bridge with a view of mt Shasta was very peaceful. The trains came through every hour, but were not too loud, we had fun watching them go by at the end of the bridge. Plenty of space between campsites. Blackberries are plentiful during the right time of year. For overnight camping, very nice. The very large trees made me a little nervous, limbs above the campsite could fall in some sites. Fish, tadpoles, and wildlife in the creek, and sacramento river. We had a great time.< /Review>< user_id>

< Text>
I am totally surprised and satisfied up to this point. I had called alot of different storage facilities before I even got around to Extra Space Storage and was not impressed with the customer service I received. I happened upon E.S.S and the lady (Tina,I believe was her name, I might be wrong) was not only extrodinarily kind and polite but extremely efficient and went above and beyond by not only finding me storage that was close by, but also letting me know that there was a special going on at the moment. Which was great, because with this Pandemic that's going on right now, funds are quite tight. So she got me the special and told me that a guy named Jerry would be my contact at the storage facility. I contacted Jerry and he was Awesome too! He asked me a few questions, then had me send him the information he needed concerning my vehicle, that I wanted to store and got me set up. It was just that fast and easy. It was all terrific, because I found out I had to move my vehicle at the last moment and most other facilities didn't have any space, but E.S.S did. So I went down there and asked for Jerry. He was there, but was on the phone with another client. He waved, smiled and asked if it was alright for Vanessa to take care of my paperwork. Vanessa was just a good as Jerry and Tina. She was very cheerful and accommodating and very polite. She had me in and out of there in less than seven minutes. She took me out, showed me the facility and where I would be parking my Vehicle. The lot was very clean, organized and we'll maintained. She showed me how to enter the gate, I drop off my vehicle and was on my way. So, would I recommend this place to others? Yes I would. I wish other businesses had this type of customer services. They just made everything Super easy. When I left, everyone in the office lifted up there hand and said goodbye. Incredible!

James Barber
05/28/2020</Text>

<pictures>None</pictures><review>This is a storage facility worth checking out. I found this place online and called the toll free number and spoke to Matt. He assisted me with renting a unit for my needs on their website. I got a great web rate for the unit. While we were on the call his computer went down, this resulted in my being charged twice for the deposit, but they were happy to credit my account once I provided proof of the mistake.

All of my questions were asked and there is no real catch to the low prices you see online. You do have to get insurance protection for your valuables and it is an additional cost, but probably worth it in the long run. It's for your protection and theirs. As I was getting of the phone with Matt at the call center, I got a call right away from Charlene, who welcomed me aboard and asked if I had additional questions and offered that I come in to take a look at the unit just to be sure it was what I was looking for.

Today, I went in to take care of the financials before I moved in and met Jerry the manager. He is very cool, calm and patient. He drove me around the cute little golf cart to show me the units and space. Place is very very clean, and even though my unit is upstairs, they have a freight elevator (it is working) and a dolly in case you don't have one available. While waiting to finalize my account the power went down twice (not their fault, men were working on the premises) and Jerry just tugged along and thanked me for my patience.

They have some of the best prices around, would be hard to beat them in such a great location in San Leandro and everyone is very friendly and accommodating and they let you know everything you need to know up front. The space is open every day and even late hours should you need to move stuff in or out after 7pm.

I would recommend them to anyone looking for great rates, fast friendly service and a clean, safe area to store your belongings.<//review>< user_name>

Vanessa, an associate at the location, soon after followed up with me with a phone call. <username>Gina Balan< /username>< Review>
My whole experience with this location and it's staff has been wonderful.  I initially made my reservation online for a 5X10 space, thinking that it would be enough for the stuff that I had.  Once I made my reservation online, I immediately received a phone call from the Site Manager, Jerry.  He was very friendly and provided me with all the information I needed.  We discussed what I was going to be storing and determined that I needed a bigger unit.  We set up a time to meet and I was on my way from San Diego.  I did run into a little bit of a snag, but the reps assisted me and I got my unit.
The facility is clean, associates are professional and friendly, and my unit is easily accessible. I think that the location of this facility is great for me, as I am still in transition to finding a new place to live and my things are centrally located. I feel secure knowing that my personal belongings are protected.  The facility is very secure with two gated entrances, security passcodes needed to get in and out of the facility, an onsite manager, and video surveillance.
I can't reiterate it enough, that the staff at this location is great.  Thank you to Jerry and his team.  I recommend this place highly.<//Review>
